CSS = Cascading Style Sheets
CSS = appearance

It answers:
How things look
Where things sit
How they change visually

<p>hello</p>
p{
    color:red;
    font-size:20px;
}

CSS Syntax:
selector { 
  property: value;
}
selector is any paragraph or header

common selector:
p          /* tag */
.myClass   /* class */
#myId      /* id */
div p      /* child */
👉 JS uses the same selectors
document.querySelector(".myClass")


1️⃣ Universal Selector

HTML
<p>Hello</p>
<div>World</div>

CSS
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}
📌 Selects everything


2️⃣ Element (Tag) Selector

HTML
<p>This is a paragraph</p>
<p>Another paragraph</p>

CSS
p {
  color: blue;
}
📌 Selects all <p> elements


3️⃣ Class Selector (.myClass)
HTML
<div class="myClass">Box 1</div>
<div class="myClass">Box 2</div>

CSS
.myClass {
  background-color: lightgray;
  padding: 10px;
}
📌 Reusable (MOST used with JS)


4️⃣ ID Selector (#myId)
HTML
<h1 id="myId">Main Heading</h1>

CSS
#myId {
  color: darkred;
}
📌 Unique element (only ONE per page)


note:Multiple classes are space-separated
5️⃣ Multiple Classes (VIP Example)

HTML
<p class="user VIP">Premium User</p>
<p class="user">Normal User</p>

CSS
.user {
  font-size: 16px;
}

.VIP {
  color: gold;
  font-weight: bold;
}
📌 VIP gets extra styling


6️⃣ Element + Class Selector

HTML
<p class="VIP">VIP Paragraph</p>
<div class="VIP">VIP Div</div>

CSS
p.VIP {
  color: purple;
}
📌 Selects only <p> with class VIP


7️⃣ Descendant Selector (Parent Child)

HTML
<div class="container">
  <p>Inside container</p>
</div>

<p>Outside container</p>

CSS
.container p {
  color: green;
}
📌 Selects <p> inside .container


1️⃣ Direct Child Selector (>)
Meaning:
👉 “Select ONLY immediate children, not nested ones”
8️⃣ Direct Child Selector (>)
HTML
<div class="box">
  <p>Direct child</p>
  <div>
    <p>Nested child</p>
  </div>
</div>

CSS
.box > p {
  color: red;
}
📌 Only direct children


9️⃣ Attribute Selector

HTML
<input type="text">
<input type="password">

CSS
input[type="password"] {
  border: 2px solid red;
}
📌 Very useful for forms


🔟 Group Selector (Multiple)

HTML
<h1>Title</h1>
<h2>Subtitle</h2>
<p>Text</p>

CSS
h1, h2, p {
  font-family: Arial;
}
📌 Apply same style to many


1️⃣1️⃣ Pseudo-class Selector

HTML
<button>Hover me</button>

CSS
button:hover {
  background-color: black;
  color: white;
}
📌 Interaction based styling

1️⃣2️⃣ Pseudo-element Selector

HTML
<p>Hello World</p>

CSS
p::first-letter {
  font-size: 30px;
}
📌 Styles part of an element


🔑 Selector Priority (VERY IMPORTANT)
*        /* lowest */
p
.myClass
#myId    /* highest */


🤔 Why is it called pseudo?
Pseudo means:
not real, not actually there, but behaves like it is
In CSS, pseudo-classes and pseudo-elements are called “pseudo” because:
👉 They are NOT real elements or classes in HTML
👉 CSS pretends they exist, based on a condition or position

🧩 Pseudo-ELEMENTS ( :: )
They behave like fake elements
::before
::after
::first-letter
::first-line

🧠 Pseudo-CLASSES ( : )

They behave like fake states or conditions
Examples:
:hover
:focus
:active
:first-child

Example
button:hover {
  background: black;
}
There is no class called hover in HTML.

CSS is saying:
“IF the user is hovering, treat it like a class”
So it’s a pseudo-class.

🎭 Why not just call them classes or elements?

Because:
You didn’t write them in HTML
You didn’t add them manually
They appear only under certain conditions

So CSS says:
“They’re like classes/elements… but not real ones”
→ pseudo


Class vs ID
/* Class */
.box {
  background: yellow;
}

/* ID */
#header {
  height: 60px;
}

Color:
color: red;
color: #ff0000;
color: rgb(255,0,0);
255 is the intensity of that color

Text
font-size: 16px;
font-weight: bold;
text-align: center;
text-transform: uppercase;

box model:
margin--outermost
border
padding
content--- innermost

div {
  width: 200px;
  padding: 10px;
  border: 2px solid black;
  margin: 20px;
}



⚠️ display: none vs visibility: hidden
visibility: hidden;
❌ Not visible
✅ Still takes space

While:
display: none;
❌ Not visible
❌ Takes NO space


1️⃣ display: block
Meaning (plain English)
“Take the full width and start on a new line”

Examples of block elements
div
p
h1–h6
section

Example
<div class="box">Box</div>

.box {
  display: block;
  width: 200px;
  height: 100px;
  background: red;
}

What happens?
Starts on a new line
Takes full width of parent
Width & height ✅ allowed
📌 Even if content is small, it occupies the whole row.


2️⃣ display: inline
Meaning
“Stay in the same line like text”

Examples of inline elements
span
a
strong

Example
<span class="text">Hello</span>
<span class="text">World</span>

.text {
  display: inline;
  width: 200px;
  height: 100px;
  background: yellow;
}

What happens?
❌ Width ignored
❌ Height ignored
✅ Stays in same line

Background applies only around text
📌 Inline elements are text-like


3️⃣ display: inline-block (MOST IMPORTANT)
Meaning
“Behave like text BUT allow box styling”
This is a mix of block + inline

Example
<div class="card">Card 1</div>
<div class="card">Card 2</div>

.card {
  display: inline-block;
  width: 150px;
  height: 100px;
  background: lightblue;
  margin: 10px;
}

What happens?
✅ Stays in same line
✅ Width works
✅ Height works
✅ Margin & padding work

📌 Perfect for:
Buttons
Cards
Badges


4️⃣ display: none
Meaning
“Pretend this element does not exist”

Example
.hidden {
  display: none;
}

What happens?
❌ Not visible
❌ Takes NO space
❌ Removed from layout

📌 Very common with JavaScript:
element.style.display = "none";


Flexbox is a one-dimensional layout system that arranges items along a 
main axis and cross axis, allowing flexible spacing, alignment, and sizing.
Flexbox works on axes, not left/right/top/bottom.

❓ Why Flexbox even exists
Before Flexbox, people used:
float
inline-block
hacks 😵‍💫

Problems:
vertical centering was painful
equal spacing was hard
responsive layouts were messy

Flexbox was created to answer one question:
“How do I arrange items inside a container easily?”


🧭 Axes (most confusing part — let’s kill the confusion)
Main Axis
default: horizontal (row)
controlled by: flex-direction

Cross Axis
perpendicular to main axis
default: vertical


what is positioning?
Positioning decides where an element sits and how it moves relative to others.
The 5 position values
position: static;
position: relative;
position: absolute;
position: fixed;
position: sticky;

1️⃣ position: static (DEFAULT)
Meaning
“Just behave normally. Don’t move.”
This is what every element is by default.

Rules
❌ top, left, right, bottom do NOTHING
✅ Element stays in normal document flow